em. John King, whom I hadseen on the eve in a college corridor, greeted me with raised arms as if thefifty hours elapsed since our last chat had been magically blown-up intohalf a century. We were only six people in a spacious parlor, not countingtwo painted girl-children in Tyrolean dress, whose presence, identity, andvery existence have remained to this day a familiar mystery--familiar,because such zigzag cracks in the plaster are typical of the prisons orpalaces into which recrudescent derang